{
  "texts": [
    "We recall that the space C(K) is separable if (and only if) the space K is metrisable.",
    "We shall identify the space of metric currents on a compact metric space X with a subspace of C(K) for a suitable compact (metrisable) space K. This will allow us to define a \"natural\" norm on the space of currents via inheritance.",
    "Definition 3.1.",
    "Given a metric space X and k ∈ N, the metric k-compactum is the topological spaceK = K(X) = Lip b,1 (X) × [Lip 1 (X)] k, equipped with the product topology.Let X be compact.",
    "Then it follows from the considerations in Subsection 2.2 that the space K(X) is compact and metrisable."
  ]
}